<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911001-0097</DOCNO><DOCID>911001-0097.</DOCID><HL>   Guaranty Federal   Ex-Official, Law Firm   Are Sued by FDIC</HL><DATE>10/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9</SO><CO>   TIN</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>CONTAINERS andamp; PACKAGING, BAGS, CANS, BOXES (CTR)LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>LAW andamp; LEGAL ISSUES AND LEGISLATION (LAW)</NS><GV>FEDERAL DEPOSIT INSURANCE CORP. (FDC)</GV><RE>ILLINOIS (IL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   DALLAS -- The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. sued theformer chief executive officer, a lawyer and the law firm ofthe failed Guaranty Federal Savings andamp; Loan Association,seeking $60 million in damages.   In a suit filed in federal court here, the FDIC chargedthat Quinton Thompson, a former president, chief executiveand director of Guaranty, was negligent and breached hisfiduciary duties in his management of Guaranty.</LP><TEXT>   The suit also charges that Morton Poznak, a Chicagolawyer, and Mr. Poznak's firm, Schwartz andamp; Freeman,represented individual directors' interests over the thrift'sinterests, represented both borrower and lender in the sametransaction, failed to fully advise Guaranty in lending andcorporate governance activities and failed to ensure thatGuaranty's officers and directors complied with federalregulations and laws.   Guaranty, which was purchased by Paul Cheng and SimonEdward Heath in 1984, failed in mid-1988 after posting lossesof about $785.2 million, the suit says. Mr. Cheng and Mr.Heath were both sentenced to long prison terms for bank fraudand other charges, have filed for personal bankruptcy-lawprotection and are currently serving their sentences. Thethrift was sold to Temple-Inland Inc. and now operates asGuaranty Federal Savings Bank.   Mr. Thompson couldn't be reached for comment and Mr.Poznak declined comment on the suit.</TEXT></DOC>